CHAPTER 1 ‚Äî LEGAL OWNERSHIP STRUCTURE
1. Umbrella Owner: Umoya Cooperative Network (UCN)
Legal Form: Cooperative corporation or association
Role: UCN legally owns all operating entities ‚Äî not individuals.

UCN Owns:
DESEF (LLC or coop subsidiary)

OVCS (LLC)

Kumba Meta-Factory (Coop LLC)

Each of the 12 Ventures (LLCs)

Each of the 7 Platforms (LLCs or SPVs)

Navigator Estate (trust or cooperative subsidiary)

Programs (Kuzu, Songhai, etc.)

Key Legal Insight:
Under state law, only a legal person (cooperative) can own assets.
Individuals do not own these entities directly.

2. What Members Have Instead of Ownership
People have Contractual/Cooperative Rights, not equity:

Capital Accounts (not shares)

Contribution Units (CUs)

Revenue participation rights

Role-based compensation rights

Governance and veto rights (assigned by class, not ownership)

These are enforceable by contract and by cooperative bylaws.

CHAPTER 2 ‚Äî OWNERSHIP VS COMPENSATION
1. Ownership (Legal Title)
Ownership = legal control and title recognized by courts.

Held by:
UCN itself

Not held by:
Individuals or roles

Individuals receive no share certificates and no equity percentage.

2. Compensation (Financial Rights)
Compensation = economic rights to revenue distribution

This is not ownership ‚Äî it‚Äôs contractual entitlement.

Compensation comes through:

Work

Contribution

Stewardship responsibilities

Governance participation

Program outcomes

Different classes get compensated in different patterns (details next).

CHAPTER 3 ‚Äî COMPENSATION SYSTEM (ALL MEMBER CLASSES)
Core Mechanism: Contribution Units (CUs)
Every member earns Contribution Units based on:

Work performed

Scope of responsibility

Role impact

Duration of participation

CU accounts are legal financial positions ‚Äî akin to a royalty or profit pool share ‚Äî but not ownership.

Why CUs Are Better Than Equity
Feature	Traditional Equity	Contribution Units
Ownership	Yes	No
Voting Control	Yes	No
Revenue Share	Possible	Yes
Transferable	Yes	No
Legal Simplicity	Hard	Easy
Founder Lock	Common	None
CUs are legally enforceable contract rights, not equity.

