A simple spreadsheet logic you can use in Google/Excel

This explanation assumes you would use standard U.S. cooperative tax rules (Subchapter T of the Internal Revenue Code) where applicable; legal counsel and an accountant should tailor the real implementation to your specifics. 
LegalClarity

üß† TAX TREATMENT MAP ‚Äî MEMBER CLASSES
1) Worker-Members (e.g., Hires)
Kind of Income

Wages/salaries: taxable as ordinary income (W-2 or 1099)

CU-based allocations/patronage distributions: taxed as ordinary income when allocated if qualified, or when redeemed if non-qualified 
LegalClarity

Reporting

Wages ‚Üí W-2/1099

Patronage distributions ‚Üí reported on Form 1099-PATR (if >$10) and taxed on personal return 
IRS

Notes

No ownership tax basis implications because there‚Äôs no equity; CU allocations are treated as income, not capital gains.

2) Steward-Members (e.g., Partners)
Kind of Income

Stewardship compensation (if paid): ordinary income

Patronage ‚Äúrefunds‚Äù or CU distributions tied to member business/patronage: taxable as income on Form 1099-PATR 
LegalClarity

Reporting

Compensation ‚Üí W-2/1099

Patronage distributions ‚Üí Form 1099-PATR

Notes

Cooperatives can deduct patr o nage dividends under Subchapter T, but members must include them in gross income. 
LegalClarity

3) Guardian-Members (Board Members)
Kind of Income

Honorarium or CU stipends: ordinary income

If any CU distribution is tied to cooperative patronage, it‚Äôs reported as a patronage distribution. 
LegalClarity

Reporting

Cash stipends ‚Üí 1099 or W-2

Patronage allocations ‚Üí Form 1099-PATR

Notes

Even if compensated for service, this is taxed as income.

4) Sensemaking Council Members
Kind of Income

CU stipends / small distributions: ordinary income

Reporting

1099 / W-2 depending on structure

5) Kuzu / Apprentices / Future Members
Kind of Income

No income until they have a compensated role or receive patronage distributions tied to patronage activities.

üè¢ TAXES ON THE ENTITIES THEMSELVES
Cooperative Entities (UCN and cooperative-qualified subsidiaries)
Co-ops filing under Subchapter T:

File Form 1120-C

Compute taxable income like a corporation, then

Deduct patronage distributions to members, passing tax to members instead of being double taxed 
LegalClarity

Patronage dividends (qualified)

Deductible at co-op level

Taxable to members when allocated

Non-patronage income

Taxed at corporate level

Not deductible via patronage mechanism 
LegalClarity

This means cooperative margins generated from member business can be passed to members and taxed once at the member level. 
LegalClarity

üìä SPREADSHEET SIMULATION LOGIC
Here‚Äôs a simple model you can put in Excel or Google Sheets to simulate taxation and distributions:

Columns (for one entity ‚Äî repeat per entity)
A	B	C	D	E
Member Name	CU Share	Enterprise Patronage Income	Allocated Patronage Dividend	Taxable Income to Member
Formula Logic
Total CU Units = SUM(CU Share)

Allocated Patronage Dividend = (CU Share / Total CU Units) √ó Total Patronage Profit

Taxable Income (Member) = Allocated Patronage Dividend

If using qualified written notices of allocation (QWNA), member includes full allocation this year. 
LegalClarity

Entity Taxable Income

= Non-Patronage Income (after deductions) because patronage distributions are deductible up to the amount distributed to members. 
LegalClarity

Example spreadsheet formulas in Excel/Sheets:

Total_CUs = SUM(B2:B10)
AllocatedDividend = (B2 / Total_CUs) * $G$1
TaxableIncomeMember = AllocatedDividend
EntityTaxableIncome = NonPatronageIncome
Optional: Cash vs Retained Splits
If the co-op retains some income for reserves and issues nonqualified notices, those retained allocations are not deductible until redeemed; members are not taxed until redemption. 
GovInfo

HOW TO HANDLE FORM 1099-PATR
When a cooperative pays or allocates patronage dividends ‚â• $10 in a year, it must file Form 1099-PATR for each member-recipient. 
IRS

This reporting flows to the member‚Äôs personal tax return.

The cooperative reports taxing details on Form 1120-C.

MEMBERS‚Äô INDIVIDUAL TAX IMPLICATIONS (SUMMARY)
Wages/Salary ‚Üí Ordinary income, reported on W-2/1099.

CU-based allocations from patronage ‚Üí Taxable to member (Form 1099-PATR) under Subchapter T rules. 
LegalClarity

Non-patronage distributions ‚Üí Taxable at co-op level; if distributed, then treated as income to members at that time. 
LegalClarity

No double taxation for income generated and paid out under Subchapter T. 
LegalClarity

NOTES & CAUTIONS
If any entity is not treated as a cooperative (e.g., a regular LLC without cooperative election), treat distributions differently (e.g., K-1 reporting).

Subchapter T‚Äôs advantages apply only if the entity qualifies and distributes patronage-based earnings. 
LegalClarity

For entities with significant non-member business, that portion of income is taxed at the entity level. 
storage.fasb.org

