I. COOP FORM ‚Äî WHAT THIS IS
Name (working)
Umoya‚ÄìDESEF‚ÄìOVCS Cooperative Federation (UDOCF)

Type
A Federated, Multi-Stakeholder, Role-Bound Cooperative

Key properties:

Membership ‚â† control

Equity ‚â† authority

Capital ‚â† governance

Exit ‚â† punishment

This coop does not optimize for equality.
It optimizes for role fidelity and system survival.

II. MEMBERSHIP CLASSES (NOW + FUTURE)
Membership is functional, not honorary.

Class A ‚Äî Founding Steward Members
(You + early constitutional partners)

Custodians of the constitution

No unilateral authority

Highest refusal burden

Can: amend constitution (supermajority)
Cannot: override layers, appoint themselves executors

Class B ‚Äî Worker-Operators
(Hires, staff, builders)

Members by labor contribution

Role-bound voting only

No cross-layer authority

Can: vote on working conditions, process integrity
Cannot: vote on capital, doctrine, venture selection

Class C ‚Äî Domain Stewards / Partners
(P1‚ÄìP5 and successors)

Members by stewardship, not hours

Veto rights in domain only

Zero executive power

Can: halt contamination
Cannot: accelerate execution

Class D ‚Äî Board / Fiduciary Members
Members by fiduciary duty

No labor or capital interest

Sunset-bound terms

Can: pause system
Cannot: run anything

Class E ‚Äî Council / Community Members
Members by legitimacy representation

No ownership claim

No operational authority

Can: trigger review
Cannot: decide outcomes

Class F ‚Äî Capital Participants (Non-Member)
(OVCS LPs, external capital)

Explicitly not members

No votes

No pathways to membership

Capital is guests only.

Class G ‚Äî Future Members (Default)
All future members enter as:

Class B (Worker-Operator)
unless explicitly elevated by two layers above them.

No fast tracks.

III. OWNERSHIP & SURPLUS RULES
1. Ownership
Coop owns all core IP, platforms, doctrine

Ventures license, never own

Individuals own nothing portable upstream

2. Surplus Allocation (Order Matters)
System maintenance & reserves

Worker-operator dividends

Stewardship pools

Commons reinvestment

Capital returns (if any)

Capital is last, always.

3. No Buy-Outs
Membership is not saleable

Equity cannot be bought

Exit = withdrawal, not liquidation

IV. AUTHORITY & VOTING MODEL
One Member ‚â† One Vote
Voting is scope-limited.

Matter	Who Votes
Working conditions	Class B
Doctrine	Class A + C
Capital activation	Board + Stewards
Platform activation	Stewards only
Constitution change	A + supermajority C
Execution details	No voting (assigned roles)
If you are not responsible, you do not vote.

V. ONBOARDING, PROGRESSION, EXIT
Onboarding (All Members)
Charter reading (mandatory)

Role boundary exam (pass/fail)

Explicit refusal rights acceptance

Exit clause acknowledged

No one joins ‚Äúto figure it out.‚Äù

Progression
Progression = more constraint, not more power

Elevation requires:

demonstrated refusal behavior

no authority violations

endorsement by two disjoint classes

Exit (Sacred Rule)
Any member may exit:

without justification

without retaliation

without loss of vested cooperative interest

Exit interviews are optional and non-binding.

VI. CAPITAL COMPATIBILITY (OVCS SAFE)
OVCS interacts with the coop as:

External capital allocator

Licensee of coop outputs

Never a governor

Capital flows:

Coop ‚Üí Venture ‚Üí Market

Never reversed

If capital conditions conflict with coop constitution:

the deal dies automatically

VII. ANTI-CAPTURE / ANTI-DEGENERATION CLAUSES
Automatic Triggers
The system enters constitutional review if:

Any role accumulates cross-layer authority

Any member frames efficiency as justification

Capital timing dictates program sequencing

Founders become indispensable

Narrative coherence exceeds system coherence

Forced Reset Mechanisms
Term limits

Mandatory rotation

Randomized audits

Kill switches held by stewards, not executives

VIII. HOW THIS SCALES
This coop scales by:

replication, not growth

federation, not centralization

forkability, not monopoly

Any region, studio, or platform may:

fork under the same constitution

remain interoperable

diverge without permission

Unity is voluntary.

