üí° Notes on the Growth Curve
üìå General Assumptions
Revenue grows modestly and consistently year-over-year ‚Äî no hockey-stick assumptions.

Growth driven by gradual adoption, expanded cohorts, platform usage, and venture customer bases.

No venture ‚Äúexits‚Äù or large capital events are baked in; those would boost later years significantly.

These figures are revenue, not profit, and before cost allocations.

üìå Entity-Level Growth Logic
Umoya Society
Starts small, slowly increases as KUZU and other non-economic programs expand.

Grants and membership dues grow with reputation, but stay modest.

DESEF
Revenue from consulting and systems engineering grows as credibility increases.

Moves from project work to larger institutional engagements.

Kumba Meta-Factory
Single or a few nodes grow franchise and workshop income.

Franchise network could expand beyond Year 5 if desired, but this model assumes low deployment.

OVCS
Management fee income rises as more ventures get incubated.

Carry becomes more meaningful in later years with revenue success of ventures.

12 Ventures (Aggregate)
Most rapidly scaling category under this model.

Ventures diversify across SaaS, services, products, and subscriptions.

Aggregate revenue grows as each cohort reaches maturity.

7 Platforms
Infrastructure platforms slowly gain usage and licensing fees.

Grants and commons funding fill early gaps.

Usage accelerates as ventures adopt the platforms.

üìà Observations & Strategic Interpretation
1. Breakeven & Sustainability
The total system moves from ~$0.75M in Year 1 to ~$6M by Year 5.

By Year 6 onward, cumulative revenue consistently increases with positive momentum.

Even in low scale, the system becomes financially meaningful by mid-decade.

2. Venture & Platform Contributions
Ventures and platforms together form the bulk of future revenue starting Year 5.

This aligns with adoption curves: foundational entities enable ventures which generate larger recurring revenue.

3. Ongoing Viability
By Year 10, a ~$19M revenue ecosystem under low assumptions is robust.

This does not include capital returns (carry) that could further expand income.

