II. TAX FLOWS ‚Äî NUMERICAL EXAMPLE
Example: One Venture, One Year
Assumptions

Revenue: $10,000,000

Operating costs (wages, rent, etc.): $7,000,000

Net surplus: $3,000,000

Surplus Allocation (Per Charter)
$3,000,000 Net Surplus

‚Üí Worker Patronage (50%)     = $1,500,000
‚Üí Venture Reserves (20%)     =   $600,000
‚Üí Commons Surplus (20%)      =   $600,000
‚Üí OVCS Revenue Share (10%)   =   $300,000
Tax Treatment (US-style example)
1. Worker Wages
$7,000,000

W-2 income

Payroll tax applies

2. Worker Patronage Dividends
$1,500,000

Passed through as ordinary income to members

Deductible to coop (avoids double taxation)

3. Venture Reserves
$600,000

Retained earnings

Taxed at entity level if not deductible

4. Commons Surplus
$600,000

Paid to Commons Trust

Deductible charitable / purpose expense (if structured correctly)

Trust pays no tax (non-extractive)

5. OVCS Share
$300,000

Ordinary income to OVCS

Distributed to workers/stewards later ‚Üí taxed again at individual level

Result

No illegal tax shelter

No disguised dividends

No private inurement

III. COMPARISON: THIS VS ESOPs / DAOs / FOUNDATIONS
1. VS ESOP
Dimension	This Model	ESOP
Ownership	Direct coop membership	Trust-held shares
Control	Role-bounded	Management-heavy
Liquidity	Redeemable	Often illiquid
Incentives	Labor + surplus	Stock appreciation
Failure Mode	Drift	Executive capture
Key Difference
ESOPs centralize governance in management.
This model prevents that legally.

2. VS DAO
Dimension	This Model	DAO
Legal standing	Fully recognized	Often ambiguous
Liability	Contained	Often unlimited
Voting	Role-scoped	Token-weighted
Equity	Real, regulated	Pseudo-equity
IRS view	Understandable	Hostile/uncertain
Key Difference
DAOs collapse power into capital.
This collapses capital into bounded roles.

3. VS Foundation-Owned Companies
Dimension	This Model	Foundation Model
Control	Distributed	Centralized
Succession	Designed-in	Trustee-dependent
Innovation	High	Often conservative
Risk	Fragmented	Concentrated
Key Difference
Foundations replace owners with trustees.
You replaced owners with constraints.

