III. CAPITAL REFUSAL POLICY
(Direct, public artifact, legally publishable ‚Äî no fiction)

CAPITAL REFUSAL POLICY
For the Commons Cooperative Federation (CCF)

Purpose:
To establish clear, binding restrictions on capital sources and financial structures that would compromise cooperatively shared ownership, prevent capture, and preserve constitutional integrity over time.

1. Capital Classes Refused
The CCF and all subsidiary entities (ventures, platforms, programs) shall not accept:

Traditional Venture Capital Equity

No preferred stock

No convertible instruments

No governance-linked shares

Tokenized Equity (Speculative or Voting)

No crypto-token ownership

No governance token issuance

Control-Linked Debt (Debt + Control Rights)

No debt that confers governance

No performance-triggered equity conversion

Government Equity Stakes with Oversight Power

No ‚Äúgolden share‚Äù

No regulatory board seats

Corporate Strategic Capital Requiring Operational Influence

No board appointed by non-cooperative stakeholders

No veto rights held externally

2. Allowed Capital
The CCF and subsidiary entities may accept:

Revenue-Based Financing (RBF)

Non-voting

Fixed repayment multiple

Cooperative Member Capital

Redeemable

Capped return

No transfer of control

Program-Related Investments (PRI)

From aligned nonprofits/foundations

Mission-aligned, non-controlling

Commons Bonds

Fixed return

No governance rights

Strategic Offtake / Customer Prepayments

Service purchase commitments

Non-equity

3. Governance Protections
Any proposed capital instrument must be reviewed and approved under the CCF Capital Boundaries Process, which requires:

Class B Steward Concurrence

Board Non-Interference Certification

Council Observation Statement

Transparency to all Coop Members

No capital form shall grant:

Board seats

Veto authority

Excessive control

De facto operational power

4. Enforcement
Violations of this policy entitle:

Immediate removal of instrument

Nullification of governance clauses

Transfer of proceeds back to a non-extractive account

Public reporting

5. Revision Protocol
This policy can be amended only through:

75% approval of all Class A + B members

Approval of Board Boundary Chair

No veto from Council Class

Final Lines
The Commons must remain capturable by all, capturable by none.
This policy ensures capital fuels cooperation, not control.

