III. TAX IMPACT SIMULATIONS
Tax profiles differ by region. Below are three jurisdiction examples.

A) UNITED STATES (Coop & Nonprofit Cosmos)
Venture (Worker Coop)
Wages taxed per payroll

Patronage dividends deductible to entity

No double taxation

State tax varies

Example Year 3

Revenue: 15M

Net surplus: 3.1M

Taxable surplus (after patronage): potentially $0 if fully allocated

Net cash retention high

OVCS
Taxed on surplus after expenses

Studio fees taxed as ordinary income

Cooperative structure minimizes tax drag

Commons Trust
Exempt as purpose asset lock

Receives deductible allocations

Umoya (501c3 or similar)
Grants typically non-taxable

B) EUROPEAN UNION (coops + foundations)
Common treatment:

Worker coops: favorable tax in some states

Platforms: VAT applies

Foundations: tax-exempt if charitable

Commons Trust: long-term asset lock

Key point:
VAT may apply to platform services; taxable profits depend on local law.

C) AFRICA (varying regimes)
General pattern:

Worker coops taxed as regular entities

Some countries allow cooperative tax benefits

Foundation/Trusts may be exempt

Model:
Net tax burden similar to small enterprise; careful structure avoids punitive corporate tax.

